SIMPLE: notion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Notion
<hw>No"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[L. <ets>notio</ets>, fr.
<ets>noscere</ets> to know: cf. F. <ets>notion</ets>. See
<er>Know</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mental apprehension of whatever
may be known or imagined; an idea; a conception; more properly, a
general or universal conception, as distinguishable or definable by
marks or <xex>notae</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What hath been generally agreed on, I content myself to assume
under the <qex>notion</qex> of principles.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I.
Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Few agree in their <qex>notions</qex> about these words.</q>
<rj><qau>Cheyne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>notion</qex> of hunger, cold, sound, color, thought,
wish, or fear which is in the mind, is called the ⟦ldquo⟧idea⟦rdquo⟧ of
hunger, cold, etc.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Notion</qex>, again, signifies either the act of
apprehending, signalizing, that is, the remarking or taking note of, the
various notes, marks, or characters of an object which its qualities
afford, or the result of that act.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sentiment; an opinion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The extravagant <qex>notion</qex> they entertain of
themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A perverse will easily collects together a system of
<qex>notions</qex> to justify itself in its obliquity.</q> <rj><qau>J.
H. Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sense; mind.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An invention; an ingenious device; a knickknack;
<as>as, Yankee <ex>notions</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Inclination; intention; disposition; <as>as, I have
a <ex>notion</ex> to do it</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Miscellaneous small objects; sundries; -- usually
referring to articles displayed together for sale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Notional</ent>⟦br⟧
